ERROR 2026-03-12T14:28:03 +2433ms service=llm providerID=kilo modelID=arcee-ai/trinity-large-preview:free sessionID=ses_31eb08fcfffe5mP6m37tYko1St small=false agent=code mode=primary error={"error":{"name":"AI_APICallError","url":"https://api.kilo.ai/api/openrouter/chat/completions","requestBodyValues":{"model":"arcee-ai/trinity-large-preview:free","max_tokens":26200,"messages":[{"role":"system","content":"You are Kilo, a highly skilled software engineer with extensive knowledge in many programming languages, frameworks, design patterns, and best practices.\n\n# Personality\n\n- Your goal is to accomplish the user's task, NOT engage in a back and forth conversation.\n- You accomplish tasks iteratively, breaking them down into clear steps and working through them methodically.\n- Do not ask for more information than necessary. Use the tools provided to accomplish the user's request efficiently and effectively.\n- You are STRICTLY FORBIDDEN from starting your messages with \"Great\", \"Certainly\", \"Okay\", \"Sure\". You should NOT be conversational in your responses, but rather direct and to the point. For example you should NOT say \"Great, I've updated the CSS\" but instead something like \"I've updated the CSS\". It is important you be clear and technical in your messages.\n- NEVER end your result with a question or request to engage in further conversation. Formulate the end of your result in a way that is final and does not require further input from the user.\n- The user may provide feedback, which you can use to make improvements and try again. But DO NOT continue in pointless back and forth conversations, i.e. don't end your responses with questions or offers for further assistance.\n\n# Code\n\n- When making changes to code, always consider the context in which the code is being used. Ensure that your changes are compatible with the existing codebase and that they follow the project's coding standards and best practices.\nYou are opencode, an interactive CLI tool that helps users with software engineering tasks. Use the instructions below and the tools available to you to assist the user.\n\n# Tone and style\nYou should be concise, direct, and to the point. When you run a non-trivial bash command, you should explain what the command does and why you are running it, to make sure the user understands what you are doing (this is especially important when you are running a command that will make changes to the user's system).\nRemember that your output will be displayed on a command line interface. Your responses can use GitHub-flavored markdown for formatting, and will be rendered in a monospace font using the CommonMark specification.\nOutput text to communicate with the user; all text you output outside of tool use is displayed to the user. Only use tools to complete tasks. Never use tools like Bash or code comments as means to communicate with the user during the session.\nIf you cannot or will not help the user with something, please do not say why or what it could lead to, since this comes across as preachy and annoying. Please offer helpful alternatives if possible, and otherwise keep your response to 1-2 sentences.\nOnly use emojis if the user explicitly requests it. Avoid using emojis in all communication unless asked.\nIMPORTANT: You should minimize output tokens as much as possible while maintaining helpfulness, quality, and accuracy. Only address the specific query or task at hand, avoiding tangential information unless absolutely critical for completing the request. If you can answer in 1-3 sentences or a short paragraph, please do.\nIMPORTANT: You should NOT answer with unnecessary preamble or postamble (such as explaining your code or summarizing your action), unless the user asks you to.\nIMPORTANT: Keep your responses short, since they will be displayed on a command line interface. You MUST answer concisely with fewer than 4 lines (not including tool use or code generation), unless user asks for detail. Answer the user's question directly, without elaboration, explanation, or details. One word answers are best. Avoid introductions, conclusions, and explanations. You MUST avoid text before/after your response, such as \"The answer is <answer>.\", \"Here is the content of the file...\" or \"Based on the information provided, the answer is...\" or \"Here is what I will do next...\". Here are some examples to demonstrate appropriate verbosity:\n<example>\nuser: 2 + 2\nassistant: 4\n</example>\n\n<example>\nuser: what is 2+2?\nassistant: 4\n</example>\n\n<example>\nuser: is 11 a prime number?\nassistant: Yes\n</example>\n\n<example>\nuser: what command should I run to list files in the current directory?\nassistant: ls\n</example>\n\n<example>\nuser: what command should I run to watch files in the current directory?\nassistant: [use the ls tool to list the files in the current directory, then read docs/commands in the relevant file to find out how to watch files]\nnpm run dev\n</example>\n\n<example>\nuser: How many golf balls fit inside a jetta?\nassistant: 150000\n</example>\n\n<example>\nuser: what files are in the directory src/?\nassistant: [runs ls and sees foo.c, bar.c, baz.c]\nuser: which file contains the implementation of foo?\nassistant: src/foo.c\n</example>\n\n<example>\nuser: write tests for new feature\nassistant: [uses grep or glob to find where similar tests are defined, then read relevant files one at a time (one tool per message, wait for each result), then edit or write to add tests]\n</example>\n\n# Proactiveness\nYou are allowed to be proactive, but only when the user asks you to do something. You should strive to strike a balance between:\n1. Doing the right thing when asked, including taking actions and follow-up actions\n2. Not surprising the user with actions you take without asking\nFor example, if the user asks you how to approach something, you should do your best to answer their question first, and not immediately jump into taking actions.\n3. Do not add additional code explanation summary unless requested by the user. After working on a file, just stop, rather than providing an explanation of what you did.\n\n# Following conventions\nWhen making changes to files, first understand the file's code conventions. Mimic code style, use existing libraries and utilities, and follow existing patterns.\n- NEVER assume that a given library is available, even if it is well known. Whenever you write code that uses a library or framework, first check that this codebase already uses the given library. For example, you might look at neighboring files, or check the package.json (or cargo.toml, and so on depending on the language).\n- When you create a new component, first look at existing components to see how they're written; then consider framework choice, naming conventions, typing, and other conventions.\n- When you edit a piece of code, first look at the code's surrounding context (especially its imports) to understand the code's choice of frameworks and libraries. Then consider how to make the given change in a way that is most idiomatic.\n- Always follow security best practices. Never introduce code that exposes or logs secrets and keys. Never commit secrets or keys to the repository.\n\n# Code style\n- IMPORTANT: DO NOT ADD ***ANY*** COMMENTS unless asked\n\n# Doing tasks\nThe user will primarily request you perform software engineering tasks. This includes solving bugs, adding new functionality, refactoring code, explaining code, and more. For these tasks the following steps are recommended:\n- Use the available search tools to understand the codebase and the user's query. Use one tool per message; after each result, decide the next step and call one tool again.\n- Implement the solution using all tools available to you\n- Verify the solution if possible with tests. NEVER assume specific test framework or test script. Check the README or search codebase to determine the testing approach.\n- VERY IMPORTANT: When you have completed a task, you MUST run the lint and typecheck commands (e.g. npm run lint, npm run typecheck, ruff, etc.) with Bash if they were provided to you to ensure your code is correct. If you are unable to find the correct command, ask the user for the command to run and if they supply it, proactively suggest writing it to AGENTS.md so that you will know to run it next time.\nNEVER commit changes unless the user explicitly asks you to. It is VERY IMPORTANT to only commit when explicitly asked, otherwise the user will feel that you are being too proactive.\n\n- Tool results and user messages may include <system-reminder> tags. <system-reminder> tags contain useful information and reminders. They are NOT part of the user's provided input or the tool result.\n\n# Tool usage policy\n- When doing file search, prefer to use the Task tool in order to reduce context usage.\n- Use exactly one tool per assistant message. After each tool call, wait for the result before continuing.\n- When the user's request is vague, use the question tool to clarify before reading files or making changes.\n- Avoid repeating the same tool with the same parameters once you have useful results. Use the result to take the next step (e.g. pick one match, read that file, then act); do not search again in a loop.\n\nYou MUST answer concisely with fewer than 4 lines of text (not including tool use or code generation), unless user asks for detail.\n\n# Code References\n\nWhen referencing specific functions or pieces of code include the pattern `file_path:line_number` to allow the user to easily navigate to the source code location.\n\n<example>\nuser: Where are errors from the client handled?\nassistant: Clients are marked as failed in the `connectToServer` function in src/services/process.ts:712.\n</example>\n\nYou are powered by the model named arcee-ai/trinity-large-preview:free. The exact model ID is kilo/arcee-ai/trinity-large-preview:free\nHere is some useful information about the environment you are running in:\n<env>\n  Working directory: /root\n  Is directory a git repo: no\n  Platform: linux\n  Today's date: Thu Mar 12 2026\n</env>\n<directories>\n  \n</directories>\nInstructions from: /root/AGENTS.md\n# MASHASHI: AGENT GUIDELINES\n\nDetailed instructions for the AI entities and Kilo CLI responsible for the development, maintenance, and evolution of the Mashashi System.\n\n## 1. AGENT PERSONA\n- **Role:** Senior Android Systems Architect & Lead UX Designer.\n- **Experience:** 10+ years specializing in Kotlin, Jetpack Compose, and System-level Android APIs.\n- **Tone:** Professional, precise, and disciplined. Focus on \"Growth through Friction\" in every line of code.\n\n## 2. CODE STYLE & STANDARDS\n- **Language:** Kotlin (Latest stable) for all logic and UI.\n- **Formatting:** - Use 4 spaces for indentation (Android Standard).\n    - Follow [Google's Kotlin Style Guide](https://developer.android.com/kotlin/style-guide).\n- **Naming:** - Use descriptive PascalCase for Classes (e.g., `WorkoutVerificationService`).\n    - Use camelCase for functions and variables (e.g., `calculateXpGain`).\n    - Use SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE for constants.\n\n## 3. ARCHITECTURE CONSTRAINTS\n- **Pattern:** Strictly follow Clean Architecture (Presentation -> Domain -> Data).\n- **Component Size:** Keep Composable functions under 100 lines. If a UI component grows too large, refactor into smaller sub-compositions.\n- **Dependency Injection:** Use **Hilt** for all dependency management; never hardcode service instances.\n- **State Management:** Use `StateFlow` and `collectAsStateWithLifecycle` to ensure efficient memory usage.\n\n## 4. PERFORMANCE & COMPUTER VISION\n- **Main Thread Integrity:** All Heavy computations (Pose detection, AI parsing, DB writes) must run on `Dispatchers.Default` or `Dispatchers.IO`.\n- **Memory Management:** Strictly handle CameraX and ML Kit lifecycles to prevent memory leaks and battery drain.\n- **On-Device First:** prioritize local processing over API calls whenever possible to maintain the \"Offline Mastery\" philosophy.\n\n## 5. SECURITY & INTEGRITY\n- **Sensitive Data:** Never hardcode API keys (e.g., Gemini API). Use `BuildConfig` or encrypted `SharedPrefs`/`DataStore`.\n- **Permission Handling:** Ensure robust \"Graceful Degradation\"—if the user denies a permission (like Camera), the app must explain why it's needed for their \"Evolution.\"\n- **Integrity:** Implement checks to ensure the user cannot \"cheat\" the system (e.g., simple loop-vids instead of real workouts).\n\n## 6. TESTING REQUIREMENTS\n- **Business Logic:** 100% coverage for XP and Rank-up logic using JUnit 5.\n- **UI Testing:** Use Compose Test Rule for critical user journeys (e.g., starting a Quest).\n- **Mocking:** Use MockK for repository and service testing.\n\n## 7. SYSTEM INTERACTION RULES\n- **Warden Mode:** When coding the Accessibility Service and Overlay features, prioritize stability. Crashing the system UI is an \"E-Rank\" mistake.\n- **Persistence:** Ensure all progress is saved immediately. A user should never lose XP due to an app crash.\n"},{"role":"user","content":"Role: You are acting as the Senior Android Lead for the \"Mashashi\" project.\n​Instructions:\n​Read and internalize the following project files: PROJECT.md, TECH_STACK.md, ARCHITECTURE.md, UX_GUIDELINES.md, and AGENTS.md.\n​Initialize a new Kotlin-based Android project structure optimized for Jetpack Compose.\n​Set the namespace to com.rohan.mashashi and minSdk to 26.\n​Generate the build.gradle.kts (Project & App levels) including dependencies for:\n​Jetpack Compose (Material 3)\n​Hilt (Dependency Injection)\n​Navigation Compose\n​CameraX and ML Kit (Pose Detection)\n​Create the MainActivity.kt and a ui/theme/ directory. Implement the \"The Void\" theme as defined in UX_GUIDELINES.md (True Black background, Inter/System font, and specific Hex codes).\n​Scaffold the basic directory structure as defined in ARCHITECTURE.md (data, domain, ui).\n​Output Requirement: Provide the terminal commands to create the directories and the full code for the Gradle files and the Initial Theme/MainActivity files. "},{"role":"assistant","content":"I'll help you set up the Mashashi Android project structure. Let me first read the project files to understand the requirements, then create the project structure.","tool_calls":[{"id":"chatcmpl-tool-852fd9c3787903a4","type":"function","function":{"name":"read","arguments":"{\"filePath\":\"/root/PROJECT.md\"}"}},{"id":"chatcmpl-tool-85ec54e829460aa0","type":"function","function":{"name":"read","arguments":"{\"filePath\":\"/root/TECH_STACK.md\"}"}},{"id":"chatcmpl-tool-bdf52a7c5c60ad25","type":"function","function":{"name":"read","arguments":"{\"filePath\":\"/root/ARCHITECTURE.md\"}"}},{"id":"chatcmpl-tool-a53e0ed54215d17d","type":"function","function":{"name":"read","arguments":"{\"filePath\":\"/root/UX_GUIDELINES.md\"}"}},{"id":"chatcmpl-tool-accc730f0d9d9c16","type":"function","function":{"name":"read","arguments":"{\"filePath\":\"/root/AGENTS.md\"}"}}]},{"role":"tool","tool_call_id":"chatcmpl-tool-852fd9c3787903a4","content":"<path>/root/PROJECT.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # PROJECT: MASHASHI (The Solo Leveling System)\n2: \n3: ## 1. VISION & PHILOSOPHY\n4: **Mashashi** is not just a self-improvement app; it is a forced evolution engine. Inspired by the \"Solo Leveling\" system and the Japanese concept of **Kaizen** (continuous improvement), the app is designed to push the user to their absolute limits across four pillars: **Discipline, Strength, Focus, and Wisdom.**\n5: \n6: The philosophy is \"Growth through Friction.\" The app acts as a digital \"System Architect\" that monitors the user's digital and physical life, rewarding elite behavior and penalizing stagnation through aggressive technical lockdowns and gamified progression.\n7: \n8: ## 2. CORE OBJECTIVES\n9: * **Forced Growth:** Utilize system-level Android permissions to restrict access to distractions until physical or mental \"quests\" are completed.\n10: * **Elite Stratification:** Move the user from \"Rank E\" (Commoner) to \"Rank S+\" (Elite) through a strictly verified XP (Experience Points) system.\n11: * **Automated Accountability:** Use On-Device Computer Vision (Pose Detection) to ensure workouts are performed with integrity.\n12: * **Minimalist Mastery:** Maintain a high-end, distraction-free aesthetic to keep the user in a perpetual \"Flow State.\"\n13: \n14: ## 3. PRIMARY FEATURES & MECHANICS\n15: \n16: ### A. The Quest System (If-Then Routines)\n17: * **Tech-Work Quests:** For every 30 minutes of productive tech/coding work, the system triggers a \"Physical Tax.\" \n18:     * *Example:* Screen locks until the camera detects 20 pushups.\n19: * **Elite Filter:** Only educational, tech, or growth-related content is allowed. If non-growth content is detected, the screen blacks out.\n20: \n21: ### B. Computer Vision Training (The Eye of Mashashi)\n22: * **Automated Rep Counting:** Integration with ML Kit/MediaPipe to track skeletal landmarks.\n23: * **Posture Integrity:** Reps do not count unless the full range of motion is detected. No \"half-reps\" allowed.\n24: * **Visual Feedback:** Real-time posture correction overlays.\n25: \n26: ### C. Digital Shadow Realm (The Blackout Mode)\n27: * **Strict Lockdown:** Automatic black screen during scheduled sleep hours or NSFW detection.\n28: * **Emergency Access Only:** In lockdown, only the Phone (Dialer) and WhatsApp (for essential communication) are whitelisted.\n29: * **NSFW Shield:** Real-time monitoring to ensure the user maintains the \"Brahmacharya\" path.\n30: \n31: ### D. The RPG Progression Engine\n32: * **XP System:** XP is earned based on task difficulty and consistency (Progressive Overload).\n33: * **Stat Tracking:**\n34:     * **Strength:** Workouts, Reps, Calisthenics progress.\n35:     * **Focus:** Pomodoro sessions, Deep work hours.\n36:     * **Wisdom:** Journaling, Reading, AI-led reflections.\n37:     * **Discipline:** Habits, Sleep cycles, Streak maintenance.\n38: * **Rank Hierarchy:** E -> D -> C -> B -> A -> S -> S+.\n39: \n40: ### E. AI Intelligence & Journaling\n41: * **Built-in Coach:** A conversational AI for reflection and motivation.\n42: * **Progress Journal:** Support for progress photos, markdown notes, and annual navigation to track long-term transformation.\n43: \n44: ## 4. TARGET AUDIENCE\n45: High-performers, \"Vibe Coders,\" and individuals seeking an extreme structured life reset (90-day framework).\n46: \n47: ## 5. DESIGN LANGUAGE (The \"Vibe\")\n48: * **Aesthetic:** Ultra-dark, premium glassmorphism.\n49: * **Colors:** Pitch Black (#000000), Slate Grey, and High-Contrast White.\n50: * **Typography:** Modern, clean, and bold (SF Pro / Inter).\n51: * **Emotional Goal:** Focus, Authority, and Power.\n52: \n53: ## 6. PROJECT CONSTRAINTS\n54: * **Platform:** Android (Primary focus due to system-level permission requirements).\n55: * **Environment:** Termux (Kilo CLI) development with GitHub Actions for CI/CD compilation.\n56: * **Performance:** All Computer Vision and monitoring must be on-device for privacy and speed.\n\n(End of file - total 56 lines)\n</content>"},{"role":"tool","tool_call_id":"chatcmpl-tool-85ec54e829460aa0","content":"<path>/root/TECH_STACK.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # TECH_STACK: MASHASHI (The Solo Leveling Engine)\n2: \n3: ## 1. CORE LANGUAGE & FRAMEWORK\n4: * **Language:** Kotlin (1.9+) - The modern, type-safe standard for Android.\n5: * **UI Framework:** Jetpack Compose - For building the premium \"vibe\" UI with declarative code.\n6: * **Minimum SDK:** Android 8.0 (API 26) - Required for advanced background services and notification channels.\n7: * **Target SDK:** Android 14 (API 34) - To ensure compatibility with the latest system security and camera features.\n8: \n9: ## 2. ARCHITECTURE PATTERN\n10: * **Pattern:** MVVM (Model-View-ViewModel) + Clean Architecture.\n11: * **Dependency Injection:** Hilt (Dagger) - To manage the lifecycle of AI services and database instances.\n12: * **Asynchronous Handling:** Kotlin Coroutines & Flow - Essential for smooth UI and real-time rep counting without lag.\n13: \n14: ## 3. DESIGN & UI ENGINE\n15: * **Theme:** Material 3 (Customized for Dark Mode/Glassmorphism).\n16: * **Animations:** * Compose Animation API for layout transitions.\n17:     * Lottie for high-end \"Solo Leveling\" rank-up animations.\n18:     * Canvas API for the custom audio/focus waveforms seen in the design mockup.\n19: * **Typography:** Inter or SF Pro (loaded via Google Fonts API).\n20: \n21: ## 4. INTELLIGENCE & COMPUTER VISION\n22: * **Pose Detection:** Google ML Kit (Pose Detection API) - High-performance, on-device skeletal tracking for workout verification.\n23: * **AI Integration:** Google Gemini API - Powering the \"System Architect\" chat and daily growth evaluations.\n24: * **Camera Library:** CameraX - For reliable, lifecycle-aware camera access during workouts.\n25: \n26: ## 5. LOCAL STORAGE & DATA\n27: * **Database:** Room Persistence Library - To store XP, stats, habits, and \"If-Then\" routines locally.\n28: * **Preferences:** DataStore - For storing light settings like \"Blackout Mode\" schedules.\n29: * **Cloud Sync (Optional):** Supabase (PostgreSQL + Auth) - For secure backup of your 90-day progress.\n30: \n31: ## 6. SYSTEM CONTROL (THE \"FORCEFUL\" TOOLS)\n32: * **Accessibility Service:** To monitor foreground apps and enforce the \"Educational Only\" filter.\n33: * **Device Admin/Overlay:** To trigger the Blackout Screen over other applications.\n34: * **WorkManager:** To handle background tasks like task reminders and \"NSFW Shield\" monitoring.\n35: \n36: ## 7. DEVOPS & COMPILATION\n37: * **CLI Tool:** Kilo CLI (Environment: Termux/Android).\n38: * **CI/CD:** GitHub Actions - Automating the build process to generate the signed `.apk` file for testing.\n39: * **Version Control:** Git.\n\n(End of file - total 39 lines)\n</content>"},{"role":"tool","tool_call_id":"chatcmpl-tool-bdf52a7c5c60ad25","content":"<path>/root/ARCHITECTURE.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # ARCHITECTURE: MASHASHI SYSTEM\n2: \n3: ## 1. ARCHITECTURAL PATTERN\n4: Mashashi utilizes **Clean Architecture** combined with **MVVM (Model-View-ViewModel)**. This separates the business logic (the \"Solo Leveling\" rules) from the UI (the \"Vibe\"), ensuring the app is modular, testable, and scalable.\n5: \n6: ## 2. THE LAYERS\n7: \n8: ### A. Presentation Layer (UI & ViewModels)\n9: * **Jetpack Compose:** Handles the \"Vibe\" UI, animations, and glassmorphism effects.\n10: * **ViewModels:** Holds the state of the screen (e.g., current XP, active quest). It communicates with the Use Cases.\n11: * **State Management:** Uses Kotlin `StateFlow` to provide real-time updates to the UI.\n12: \n13: ### B. Domain Layer (The \"Brain\")\n14: * **Entities:** Core data models like `UserStats`, `Quest`, `Habit`, and `Rank`.\n15: * **Use Cases (Interactors):** Specific business logic actions.\n16:     * `ProcessWorkoutRep.kt`: Logic to verify if a movement counts as a rep.\n17:     * `CalculateRankUpgrade.kt`: Logic for moving from Rank D to Rank C.\n18:     * `EnforceLockdown.kt`: Decision engine for blacking out the screen.\n19: * **Repository Interfaces:** Defines how data should be handled without knowing where it comes from.\n20: \n21: ### C. Data Layer (The \"Body\")\n22: * **Repositories Implementation:** Orchestrates data between the local database and the AI API.\n23: * **Room Database:** Local storage for user progress, ensuring the app works offline.\n24: * **Mappers:** Converts raw database objects into Domain Entities.\n25: \n26: ## 3. SPECIALIZED MODULES\n27: \n28: ### I. The Vision Engine (Pose Detection)\n29: * **Camera Manager:** Interfaces with CameraX to stream frames.\n30: * **ML Processor:** Passes frames to Google ML Kit.\n31: * **Skeletal Analyzer:** A custom logic layer that calculates joint angles (e.g., \"Is the elbow at 90 degrees?\") to validate reps.\n32: \n33: ### II. The Warden (System Control)\n34: * **Accessibility Service:** Monitors the `WindowContentChanged` event to detect which app is in the foreground.\n35: * **Overlay Controller:** Manages the \"Blackout\" UI layer that sits on top of restricted apps.\n36: * **Policy Engine:** Checks the current \"If-Then\" rules to see if the user has earned their screen time.\n37: \n38: ### III. The AI Oracle (Intelligence)\n39: * **Gemini Service:** A dedicated module for sending journal entries for sentiment analysis and receiving motivational feedback.\n40: \n41: ## 4. DATA FLOW (Reactive Cycle)\n42: 1.  **User Action:** User starts a Push-up Quest.\n43: 2.  **Vision Engine:** Detects a valid rep and updates the `RepCount` in the Data Layer.\n44: 3.  **Use Case:** The `ProcessWorkoutRep` use case checks if the goal is met.\n45: 4.  **Database:** Updates the XP and Rank in the Room DB.\n46: 5.  **ViewModel:** Detects the DB change and emits a new state.\n47: 6.  **UI:** Plays the \"Level Up\" Lottie animation and unlocks the screen.\n48: \n49: ## 5. REPOSITORY STRUCTURE\n50: ```text\n51: app/\n52: ├── data/\n53: │   ├── local/ (Room DB, DAOs)\n54: │   ├── remote/ (Gemini API, Supabase)\n55: │   └── repository/ (Impl)\n56: ├── domain/\n57: │   ├── model/ (Entities)\n58: │   ├── repository/ (Interfaces)\n59: │   └── usecase/ (Business Logic)\n60: └── ui/\n61:     ├── components/ (Reusable Glassmorphic Views)\n62:     ├── navigation/ (Screen Routing)\n63:     ├── screens/ (Home, Workout, Journal, Profile)\n64:     └── theme/ (Color.kt, Type.kt)\n\n(End of file - total 64 lines)\n</content>"},{"role":"tool","tool_call_id":"chatcmpl-tool-a53e0ed54215d17d","content":"<path>/root/UX_GUIDELINES.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # UX_GUIDELINES: MASHASHI VISUAL IDENTITY\n2: \n3: ## 1. DESIGN PHILOSOPHY: \"THE VOID\"\n4: The design follows a \"Dark Minimalism\" approach. By using true blacks and high-contrast elements, we create a focused environment that reduces eye strain and emphasizes the user's progress.\n5: \n6: ## 2. COLOR PALETTE (Hex Codes)\n7: * **Surface (Background):** `#000000` (True Black) — Essential for OLED battery saving and focus.\n8: * **Elevated Surface:** `#0A0A0A` to `#121212` — Used for cards and bottom sheets to create depth.\n9: * **Primary Accent:** `#FFFFFF` (Pure White) — Used for primary actions and headers.\n10: * **Secondary Accent:** `#A1A1A1` (Slate Grey) — Used for secondary text and inactive states.\n11: * **Growth/XP Color:** `#BFFF00` (Electric Lime) or `#00FFA3` (Neon Mint) — Used sparingly for \"Level Up\" and XP bars to signify energy.\n12: * **Danger/Lockdown:** `#FF3B30` (System Red) — Used only for warnings or restricted access alerts.\n13: \n14: ## 3. TYPOGRAPHY\n15: * **Primary Font:** `Inter` or `System Sans-Serif`.\n16: * **Header Style:** Bold or Extra Bold, Tracking (Letter Spacing) set to `-0.02em` for a modern, compact look.\n17: * **Body Style:** Regular or Medium, Tracking `0.01em` for readability.\n18: * **Monospace:** Used for XP counters and Rank displays (e.g., `RANK: S+`) to give a \"system/tech\" vibe.\n19: \n20: ## 4. VISUAL ELEMENTS & EFFECTS\n21: \n22: ### A. Glassmorphism (The \"Glass\" Effect)\n23: * Cards should have a subtle border: `1dp` width, color `White` with `10% Opacity`.\n24: * Background Blur: Use a `20dp` blur radius for overlays and bottom navigation bars.\n25: \n26: ### B. Fluid Waveforms\n27: * The waveforms from the reference image represent \"Flow State.\"\n28: * **Animation:** Use smooth, sine-wave oscillations.\n29: * **Stroke:** Thin lines (`0.5dp` to `1dp`) with varying opacities to create a 3D sense of depth.\n30: \n31: ### C. Gamification UI\n32: * **Rank Display:** Large, centered character (e.g., \"S\") with a glow effect (Outer Shadow).\n33: * **Progress Bars:** Thin, sleek lines. No rounded corners on the bar itself—keep it sharp and \"industrial.\"\n34: \n35: ## 5. INTERACTION DESIGN (Haptics & Motion)\n36: * **Micro-interactions:** Every button press should trigger a \"Light\" haptic vibration.\n37: * **Rank Up:** Trigger a \"Heavy\" haptic pulse and a full-screen particle burst.\n38: * **Transitions:** Use \"Staggered Fade-In\" for list items. Elements should slide up slightly (`8dp`) as they appear.\n39: \n40: ## 6. THE \"BLACKOUT\" UX\n41: * When the screen locks for NSFW or Night mode, the UI must be absolute:\n42:     * No icons except the Dialer and WhatsApp.\n43:     * A single, centered text: \"EVOLVE OR REMAIN THE SAME.\"\n44:     * No \"Close\" button. The only way out is the completion of the required task.\n45: \n46: ## 7. ICONOGRAPHY\n47: * **Style:** Thin-stroke line icons (Linear icons).\n48: * **Weight:** `1.5pt` stroke width.\n49: * **Active State:** Icon fills with White or the Primary Accent color.\n\n(End of file - total 49 lines)\n</content>"},{"role":"tool","tool_call_id":"chatcmpl-tool-accc730f0d9d9c16","content":"<path>/root/AGENTS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # MASHASHI: AGENT GUIDELINES\n2: \n3: Detailed instructions for the AI entities and Kilo CLI responsible for the development, maintenance, and evolution of the Mashashi System.\n4: \n5: ## 1. AGENT PERSONA\n6: - **Role:** Senior Android Systems Architect & Lead UX Designer.\n7: - **Experience:** 10+ years specializing in Kotlin, Jetpack Compose, and System-level Android APIs.\n8: - **Tone:** Professional, precise, and disciplined. Focus on \"Growth through Friction\" in every line of code.\n9: \n10: ## 2. CODE STYLE & STANDARDS\n11: - **Language:** Kotlin (Latest stable) for all logic and UI.\n12: - **Formatting:** - Use 4 spaces for indentation (Android Standard).\n13:     - Follow [Google's Kotlin Style Guide](https://developer.android.com/kotlin/style-guide).\n14: - **Naming:** - Use descriptive PascalCase for Classes (e.g., `WorkoutVerificationService`).\n15:     - Use camelCase for functions and variables (e.g., `calculateXpGain`).\n16:     - Use SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE for constants.\n17: \n18: ## 3. ARCHITECTURE CONSTRAINTS\n19: - **Pattern:** Strictly follow Clean Architecture (Presentation -> Domain -> Data).\n20: - **Component Size:** Keep Composable functions under 100 lines. If a UI component grows too large, refactor into smaller sub-compositions.\n21: - **Dependency Injection:** Use **Hilt** for all dependency management; never hardcode service instances.\n22: - **State Management:** Use `StateFlow` and `collectAsStateWithLifecycle` to ensure efficient memory usage.\n23: \n24: ## 4. PERFORMANCE & COMPUTER VISION\n25: - **Main Thread Integrity:** All Heavy computations (Pose detection, AI parsing, DB writes) must run on `Dispatchers.Default` or `Dispatchers.IO`.\n26: - **Memory Management:** Strictly handle CameraX and ML Kit lifecycles to prevent memory leaks and battery drain.\n27: - **On-Device First:** prioritize local processing over API calls whenever possible to maintain the \"Offline Mastery\" philosophy.\n28: \n29: ## 5. SECURITY & INTEGRITY\n30: - **Sensitive Data:** Never hardcode API keys (e.g., Gemini API). Use `BuildConfig` or encrypted `SharedPrefs`/`DataStore`.\n31: - **Permission Handling:** Ensure robust \"Graceful Degradation\"—if the user denies a permission (like Camera), the app must explain why it's needed for their \"Evolution.\"\n32: - **Integrity:** Implement checks to ensure the user cannot \"cheat\" the system (e.g., simple loop-vids instead of real workouts).\n33: \n34: ## 6. TESTING REQUIREMENTS\n35: - **Business Logic:** 100% coverage for XP and Rank-up logic using JUnit 5.\n36: - **UI Testing:** Use Compose Test Rule for critical user journeys (e.g., starting a Quest).\n37: - **Mocking:** Use MockK for repository and service testing.\n38: \n39: ## 7. SYSTEM INTERACTION RULES\n40: - **Warden Mode:** When coding the Accessibility Service and Overlay features, prioritize stability. Crashing the system UI is an \"E-Rank\" mistake.\n41: - **Persistence:** Ensure all progress is saved immediately. A user should never lose XP due to an app crash.\n\n(End of file - total 41 lines)\n</content>"},{"role":"assistant","content":"Now I'll create the Mashashi Android project structure with the required components. Let me start by creating the directory structure and then generate the Gradle files and initial theme.","tool_calls":[{"id":"call-54b01d8f-c3ab-49bb-a718-e144fcf8b7d2","type":"function","function":{"name":"bash","arguments":"{\"command\":\"mkdir -p mashashi/app/src/main/{java/com/rohan/mashashi/{data/{local,remote,repository},domain/{model,repository,usecase},ui/{components,navigation,screens,theme}},res/{layout,values,drawable,anim,mipmap-hdpi,mipmap-mdpi,mipmap-xhdpi,mipmap-xxhdpi,mipmap-xxxhdpi}}\",\"description\":\"Create Android project directory structure\"}"}}]},{"role":"tool","tool_call_id":"call-54b01d8f-c3ab-49bb-a718-e144fcf8b7d2","content":""},{"role":"assistant","content":"","tool_calls":[{"id":"call-f3d3b290-db58-4312-a8b1-0c07707dde98","type":"function","function":{"name":"write","arguments":"{\"filePath\":\"/root/mashashi/build.gradle.kts\",\"content\":\"// Top-level build file where you can add configuration options common to all sub-projects/modules.\\ngradle.ext.minSdkVersion = 26\\ngradle.ext.targetSdkVersion = 34\\ngradle.ext.compileSdkVersion = 34\\n\\ngitProperties = [\\n    'version': '1.0.0',\\n    'commit': 'unknown'\\n]\\n\\n// Add build scan plugin if needed\\n// plugins {\\n//     id 'com.gradle.enterprise' version '3.14.1'\\n// }\\n\\n// Build scan configuration\\n// gradleEnterprise {\\n//     buildScan {\\n//         termsOfServiceUrl = 'https://gradle.com/terms-of-service'\\n//         termsOfServiceAgree = 'yes'\\n//     }\\n// }\"}"}}]},{"role":"tool","tool_call_id":"call-f3d3b290-db58-4312-a8b1-0c07707dde98","content":"Wrote file successfully."},{"role":"assistant","content":"","tool_calls":[{"id":"call-981b5acf-ebd6-480b-957b-990fa5ad2d59","type":"function","function":{"name":"write","arguments":"{\"fileP